Air Quality Prediction using Statistical and Machine Learning Models¶

David, Dini & Jimmy

Abstract¶

Air Quality Index (AQI) prediction provides valuable information about air quality, helps individuals take protective actions, supports environmental conservation, and assists policymakers in implementing strategies to control air pollution. This study aims to predict and forecast AQI over a one-year period using the XGBoost model. The data used for AQI prediction were obtained from the Taiwan Ministry of Environment, covering the years 2016 to 2025 and consisting of measurements from 75 monitoring stations. The air pollution predictors used in this study include SO₂, CO, O₃, PM₁₀, PM₂.₅, NO₂, NOₓ, and NO. The results showed that the average AQI prediction achieved a fairly good RMSE of 3.652. Furthermore, the one-year (2025–2026) forecast revealed a seasonal pattern across all stations, with AQI levels generally increasing during the summer months, particularly around July and August.

Main¶

Introduction¶

Air pollution represents a significant global environmental health concern, leading to 4.1 million premature deaths during 2000–2017 (Stanaway et al., 2018). To facilitate the access of the public to overall ambient air quality information for guiding their outdoor activities, the Air Quality Index (AQI) has been widely adopted (Mirabelli et al., 2020). AQI is a key indicator for assessing air quality and its associated health impacts. Accurate AQI calculations are crucial for reliable air quality assessments, but outliers in air quality data can distort these calculations, leading to inaccurate predictions (Kumar Dongre et al., 2025). In this project, we propose frameworks to characterize air quality dynamics by integrating multivariate statistical modeling and machine learning techniques, employing Taiwan’s high-density air quality monitoring networks.

(1) Data¶

Historical air quality index open data (from 2016-2025) were fetched from Ministry of Environment, Taiwan Authority (https://data.moenv.gov.tw/en/dataset/detail/AQX_P_488), which would be preprocessed in accordance to difference modeling methods and application. There are 76 data points (stations) in total, but we only consider stations in main island, where offshore station were excluded. Thus, 75 stations were used in total , stations distribution and data structure are shown as Figure 1. below.

(2.1) Simple Neural Network Model (David)

Neural network-based spatial interpolation for Air Quality Index (AQI) data from sparse monitoring stations.
Workflow:

3.Smooth values (Avoid the outliers)

Data Summary

Target variable: AQI
Predictors:
SO2: from industrial sources
CO: mainly from vehicles
PM10: dust and larger particles
PM2.5: fine particles, most health-threatening
NO2: from combustion sources
NO: from vehicle emissions
72 stations data were used, each station contains 12194 observations (after resampling)

Objectives

To obtain the continuous map of AQI values for entire Taiwan.

Neural Network Architecture

Input Layer: Receives all the information (location, time, environmental data)
Hidden Layer 1: 128 artificial neurons (initial pattern detection)
Hidden Layer 2: 256 neurons (finding more complex patterns)
Hidden Layer 3: 512 neurons (advanced pattern analysis)
Hidden Layer 4: 1,024 neurons (the "thinking center" - maximum complexity)
Hidden Layer 5: 512 neurons (pattern refinement)
Hidden Layer 6: 256 neurons (pattern consolidation)
Hidden Layer 7: 128 neurons (final pattern preparation)
Output Layer: 1 neuron (produces the air quality prediction)

Optimizer: AdamW

Learning Parameters
Learning Rate: 0.001
Beta_1: 0.9 (how much it remembers from recent lessons)
Beta_2: 0.999 (how much it remembers from long-term patterns)
Weight Decay: 0.01
Epochs: 300
Early stopping: after 20 epochs without improvement

L2 Regularization: 0.001
Dropout Regularization:
Layer 1: Ignores 20% of neurons randomly
Layer 2: Ignores 25% of neurons randomly
Layer 3: Ignores 30% of neurons randomly
Layer 4: Ignores 40% of neurons randomly (maximum dropout at the most complex layer)
Layer 5, 6, 7 → 30% , 25% , 20% , respectively

Data Splitting Strategy
Training Data: 75%
Validation Data: 15%
Test Data: 10%
Multiple performance metrics to ensure high-quality predictions:
Mean Absolute Error (MAE)
Mean Squared Error (MSE)
R-squared
Mean Absolute Percentage Error

(2.2) Forecasting AQI 24 hours using *XGBoost* (Dini)

Predict and forecast AQI over a one-year period using the XGBoost model.
Workflow:

Data Acquisition and Preprocessing

The data used in this study consist of historical records from 2016 to 2025, including AQI and air pollution indicators (SO₂, CO, O₃, PM₁₀, PM₂.₅, NO₂, NOₓ, and NO), obtained from the Taiwan Ministry of Environment (https://data.moenv.gov.tw/en/dataset/detail/AQX_P_488). The dataset includes observations from 75 monitoring stations. All zero values in both the predictors and the target variable were removed prior to further analysis, as this approach was found to be more effective and resulted in a lower RMSE compared to using linear interpolation to handle missing values.

Feature Engineering

Feature engineering plays a vital role in time series forecasting, particularly when using boosting models that do not inherently capture temporal dependencies. The forecast horizon refers to the future time period we aim to predict—ranging from short-term (under three months) to long-term (over two years). To provide temporal context, we include datetime features such as hour, day of week, month, and day of year. In addition, we engineer seasonal and trend components for selected pollutant variables (e.g., aqi_seasonal, so2_trend) to capture underlying patterns and long-term shifts in the data. Since the AQI for a given day must be predicted without using its actual values at inference time, we incorporate lag features—specifically aqi_lag1, aqi_lag24, and aqi_lag168—to represent values from 1 hour, 1 day, and 7 days prior, respectively. We also use current values of other pollutant variables (excluding aqi) as predictors. Altogether, these features—totaling 33—allow the model to learn from temporal patterns, trends, and pollution-related interactions, improving its ability to accurately forecast AQI levels.

Split Training and Testing Data

To evaluate the model's performance robustly over time, a time series cross-validation approach was applied using 5-fold expanding window splitting using TimeSeriesSplit in sklearn. To split the dataset into training and testing sets while preserving the chronological order of time series data, the TimeSeriesSplit function from the sklearn.model_selection module was used. Each test set corresponds to one year of hourly data (24 hours × 365 days). A gap of 24 hours (1 day) is introduced between the end of the training set and the start of the test set to avoid data leakage. This approach ensures that future data is never used to predict the past, maintaining the temporal integrity of the forecasting task.

Model XGBoost

For the modeling stage, we employed XGBoost (Extreme Gradient Boosting), a powerful tree-based ensemble algorithm known for its high accuracy and efficiency. XGBoost builds models sequentially using gradient boosting and includes regularization to reduce overfitting. The model was configured with the following key parameters: n_estimators=1500 to allow enough boosting rounds, learning_rate=0.01 for gradual learning, and max_depth=3 to control model complexity. We used booster='gbtree' for tree-based learners and set objective='reg:squarederror' for regression tasks. An early_stopping_rounds=50 was applied to halt training when validation performance stopped improving. This setup aimed to balance learning stability and predictive accuracy for AQI forecasting.

(3) Implement anomaly detection algorithms for identifying statistically significant pollution events. (Jimmy)¶

Apply an anomaly event detection framework to air pollutants by using Supervised Random Forest.
Workflow:

Data Preprocessing and Label

Target variable: AQI Anomaly (any pollutant exceeds 95th percentile of its values at that station)
Features: SO2, CO, O3, PM2.5, PM10, NO2
Additional temporal features: Hour of day, Month of year
Statistical features: 4-period (24-hour) rolling mean and standard deviation for each pollutant
All negative and extreme values removed, then resampled at 6-hour intervals
71 stations used, with 837,215 valid observations after cleaning and resampling

Hyperparameter Tuning

GridSearchCV was applied with TimeSeriesSplit (5 folds) to maintain temporal consistency.
Parameters tuned:
- Number of Trees (`n_estimators`): [100, 200, 300]
- Tree Depth (`max_depth`): [5, 10, 20, None]
- Minimum samples to split (`min_samples_split`): [2, 5, 10]
- Minimum samples at leaf (`min_samples_leaf`): [1, 2, 4]
Best configuration found:
→ n_estimators=100, max_depth=10, min_samples_split=2, min_samples_leaf=1

Evaluation Metrics

Binary Classification Metrics:

Special attention was paid to F1 Score to balance precision and recall under data imbalance.
Confusion matrix was used to visualize false positives and false negatives.

Results¶

(1) Neural Network Interpolation Map¶

Figure 2. Interpolation result of 2017-2019

(2) Cross Validation and Forecast Result Using XGBoost¶

The XGBoost model demonstrated good performance in predicting hourly AQI values, achieving a Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) of 3.652. This indicates a relatively good accuracy, especially considering the complexity of air quality data and its temporal variability. The model effectively captured the nonlinear relationship between AQI and eight pollutant indicators (SO₂, CO, O₃, PM₁₀, PM₂.₅, NO₂, NOₓ, and NO), aided by the inclusion of time-based features and lag variables. The feature engineering process contributed significantly to the performance improvement, allowing the model to identify short-term fluctuations and long-term trends.

Figure 3. Actual vs Predicted AQI on Validation Set

In the one-year AQI forecast for 2025–2026, a clear seasonal pattern was observed across all monitoring stations. AQI levels generally increase during the summer months, peaking around July and August, which may be attributed to increased ozone formation due to higher temperatures. Conversely, lower AQI values were seen in cooler months, particularly in winter. This seasonal trend reflects the influence of meteorological conditions and human activities on pollutant levels.

Figure 4. Forecasted AQI Values for 2025–2026

(3) AQI Anomaly Detection¶

The confusion matrix highlights the model's conservative design for detecting anomalies. Among the 438,984 test samples, the model correctly predicted 70,695 true positives (anomalous periods) and 302,556 true negatives (normal periods). The recall for the anomaly class reached 86.2%, indicating strong capability in capturing real anomaly events.

However, the model also generated 54,412 false positives — normal events misclassified as anomalies. This led to a precision of 56.5% for the anomaly class, revealing a trade-off where the model favors sensitivity over specificity. In real-world deployment, this could result in frequent alerts, which may require post-filtering or rule-based confirmation to reduce alarm fatigue.

In terms of feature contributions, the feature importance plot shows that O3, PM10, PM2.5, and SO2 were the most influential predictors. These variables directly reflect pollution severity and align with known AQI determinants. Rolling statistics (mean/std) and temporal context (hour/month) contributed marginally, suggesting the model relied more on absolute pollutant levels than patterns over time.

Figure 5. Feature Importance

Discussion¶

Gap in Monitoring Station Distribution¶

The sparse distribution of monitoring stations in Taiwan’s central mountainous region led to noticeable interpolation gaps. This spatial limitation reduced the accuracy of neural network-based AQI interpolation. Future work should consider incorporating satellite data or terrain-aware models to improve coverage.

Anomaly Labeling Scope¶

This study only labeled anomalies based on individual pollutant thresholds. While effective for detecting isolated spikes, it lacks sensitivity to complex multi-pollutant events. Incorporating composite anomaly definitions may better reflect real-world pollution episodes.

Conclusions¶

This study proposed a three-part framework to improve air quality analysis and forecasting. First, a neural network interpolation method was applied to reconstruct spatial AQI distributions from sparse monitoring stations. Second, a one-year AQI forecasting model based on XGBoost achieved strong predictive performance (average RMSE ≈ 2.9), capturing both seasonal trends and hourly fluctuations. Third, an anomaly detection module using Random Forest, combined with statistical thresholding and SMOTE resampling, successfully detected rare pollution events with high recall (86.2%) and acceptable precision (56.5%). This demonstrates the framework’s capability in recognizing short-term air quality hazards while maintaining robustness against class imbalance. While the proposed models are scalable, caution must be taken to prevent over-extrapolation and outdated predictions due to shifting pollution patterns or insufficient station coverage.

def create_time_features(df):
    """Create time-based features"""
    df = df.copy()
    df['hour'] = df.index.hour
    df['dayofweek'] = df.index.dayofweek
    df['quarter'] = df.index.quarter
    df['month'] = df.index.month
    df['year'] = df.index.year
    df['dayofyear'] = df.index.dayofyear
    df['dayofmonth'] = df.index.day
    df['weekofyear'] = df.index.isocalendar().week
    return df
In [5]:
def create_seasonal_features(train_df, target_cols):
    """Create seasonal decomposition features using only training data"""
    seasonal_features = {}
    
    for col in target_cols:
        # Decompose using only training data
        decomp = seasonal_decompose(train_df[col], period=24, model='additive', extrapolate_trend='freq')
        
        # Store seasonal patterns
        seasonal_features[f'{col}_seasonal_pattern'] = decomp.seasonal[:24].values  # 24-hour pattern
        seasonal_features[f'{col}_trend_slope'] = np.nanmean(np.diff(decomp.trend))  # average trend
    
    return seasonal_features
In [6]:
def apply_seasonal_features(df, seasonal_patterns):
    """Apply seasonal patterns to any dataframe"""
    df = df.copy()
    
    for col in selected_cols:
        # Apply 24-hour seasonal pattern
        seasonal_key = f'{col}_seasonal_pattern'
        if seasonal_key in seasonal_patterns:
            df[f'{col}_seasonal'] = [seasonal_patterns[seasonal_key][hour] for hour in df.index.hour]
        
        # Apply trend (simple linear trend based on training data)
        trend_key = f'{col}_trend_slope'
        if trend_key in seasonal_patterns:
            # Calculate days from start of training
            start_date = df.index.min()
            days_from_start = (df.index - start_date).days
            df[f'{col}_trend'] = seasonal_patterns[trend_key] * days_from_start
    
    return df
In [7]:
def create_lag_features(df, target_col, lags=[1, 24, 168]):  # 1h, 1day, 1week
    """Create lag features safely"""
    df = df.copy()
    
    for lag in lags:
        df[f'{target_col}_lag{lag}'] = df[target_col].shift(lag)
    
    return df

In [16]:
# Cross validation
from sklearn.model_selection import TimeSeriesSplit
tss = TimeSeriesSplit(n_splits=5, test_size=24*365*1, gap=24)
df_copy =train_df.copy()
df_copy=df_copy.sort_index()

fold = 0
preds = []
scores = []

for train_idx, val_idx in tss.split(df_copy):
    train_fold = df_copy.iloc[train_idx].copy()
    test_fold = df_copy.iloc[val_idx].copy()

    train_fold = create_time_features(train_fold)
    test_fold = create_time_features(test_fold)

    FEATURES = FEATURES
    TARGET = 'aqi'

    X_train = train_fold[FEATURES]
    y_train = train_fold[TARGET]

    X_test = test_fold[FEATURES]
    y_test = test_fold[TARGET]

    reg = xgb.XGBRegressor(base_score=0.5, booster='gbtree',    
                           n_estimators=1500,
                           early_stopping_rounds=50,
                           objective='reg:squarederror',
                           max_depth=3,
                           learning_rate=0.01)
    reg.fit(X_train, y_train,
            eval_set=[(X_train, y_train), (X_test, y_test)],
            verbose=100)

    y_pred = reg.predict(X_test)
    preds.append(y_pred)
    score = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
    scores.append(score)

def create_future_dates(last_date, periods=24*365):
    """
    Create a date for forecasting
    periods: number of hours for prediction (24*365 = 1 year)
    """
    future_dates = pd.date_range(
        start=last_date + timedelta(hours=1),
        periods=periods,
        freq='H'
    )
    return future_dates
In [23]:
def create_future_dataframe(future_dates, seasonal_patterns, last_known_values):
    """
    Create a dataframe for forecasting with all the necessary features
    """
    future_df = pd.DataFrame(index=future_dates)
    
    # 1. Time features (according to those used in the model)
    future_df['hour'] = future_df.index.hour
    future_df['dayofweek'] = future_df.index.dayofweek
    future_df['quarter'] = future_df.index.quarter
    future_df['month'] = future_df.index.month
    future_df['year'] = future_df.index.year
    future_df['dayofyear'] = future_df.index.dayofyear
    future_df['dayofmonth'] = future_df.index.day
    future_df['weekofyear'] = future_df.index.isocalendar().week
    
    # 2. Apply seasonal features for all pollutants
    all_pollutants = ['aqi', 'so2', 'co', 'o3', 'pm10', 'pm2.5', 'no2', 'nox', 'no']
    for pollutant in all_pollutants:
        # Apply 24-hour seasonal pattern
        seasonal_key = f'{pollutant}_seasonal_pattern'
        if seasonal_key in seasonal_patterns:
            future_df[f'{pollutant}_seasonal'] = [seasonal_patterns[seasonal_key][hour % 24] 
                                                 for hour in future_df.index.hour]
        
        # Apply trend
        trend_key = f'{pollutant}_trend_slope'
        if trend_key in seasonal_patterns:
            start_date = future_df.index.min()
            days_from_start = (future_df.index - start_date).days
            future_df[f'{pollutant}_trend'] = seasonal_patterns[trend_key] * days_from_start
    
    # 3. initialize pollutant values ​​with the last known values
    pollutants = ['so2', 'co', 'o3', 'pm10', 'pm2.5', 'no2', 'nox', 'no']
    for pollutant in pollutants:
        future_df[pollutant] = last_known_values[pollutant]
    
    # 4. Initialize aqi with the last value (will be updated in the prediction loop)
    future_df['aqi'] = last_known_values['aqi']
    
    # 5. Initialize lag features with last values
    future_df['aqi_lag1'] = last_known_values['aqi']
    future_df['aqi_lag24'] = last_known_values['aqi']  
    future_df['aqi_lag168'] = last_known_values['aqi']
    
    return future_df

def multi_step_forecast(model, future_df, features, n_steps, historical_data, seed=42):
    """
    Performing multi-step forecasting with update lag features
    """
    np.random.seed(seed)
    predictions = []
    future_df_copy = future_df.copy()
    
    # Cache column indices for efficiency
    try:
        aqi_idx = future_df_copy.columns.get_loc('aqi')  # ← Ini yang hilang!
        aqi_lag1_idx = future_df_copy.columns.get_loc('aqi_lag1')
        aqi_lag24_idx = future_df_copy.columns.get_loc('aqi_lag24')
        aqi_lag168_idx = future_df_copy.columns.get_loc('aqi_lag168')
    except KeyError as e:
        raise ValueError(f"Required column not found: {e}")
    
    historical_aqi = historical_data['aqi'].values
    
    for i in range(n_steps):
        # Update aqi value based on previous predictions
        if i > 0:
            future_df_copy.iloc[i, aqi_idx] = predictions[i-1]  # ← Sekarang menggunakan aqi_idx
        
        # Update lag features
        if i >= 1:
            future_df_copy.iloc[i, aqi_lag1_idx] = predictions[i-1]
        
        if i >= 24:
            future_df_copy.iloc[i, aqi_lag24_idx] = predictions[i-24]
        
        # for lag168
        lag168_index = len(historical_aqi) + i - 168
        if lag168_index >= 0:
            if lag168_index < len(historical_aqi):
                lag168_value = historical_aqi[lag168_index]
            else:
                pred_index = lag168_index - len(historical_aqi)
                lag168_value = predictions[pred_index]
            future_df_copy.iloc[i, aqi_lag168_idx] = lag168_value
        
        # Update pollutant values
        if i > 0:
            for pollutant in ['so2', 'co', 'o3', 'pm10', 'pm2.5', 'no2', 'nox', 'no']:
                seasonal_val = future_df_copy.iloc[i][f'{pollutant}_seasonal']
                trend_val = future_df_copy.iloc[i][f'{pollutant}_trend']
                base_val = future_df_copy.iloc[i-1][pollutant]
                
                seasonal_factor = 1 + (seasonal_val / (abs(seasonal_val) + 1)) * 0.1
                noise = np.random.normal(0, base_val * 0.02)
                
                new_val = max(0, base_val * seasonal_factor + trend_val * 0.001 + noise)
                pollutant_idx = future_df_copy.columns.get_loc(pollutant)
                future_df_copy.iloc[i, pollutant_idx] = new_val
        
        # Prediction
        X_current = future_df_copy.iloc[i:i+1][features]  # use 'features' parameter
        pred = model.predict(X_current)[0]
        predictions.append(pred)
        
        if (i + 1) % 1000 == 0:
            print(f"Progress: {i+1}/{n_steps} steps completed ({(i+1)/n_steps*100:.1f}%)")
    
    return np.array(predictions), future_df_copy

import os

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

# Folder and parameters
data_folder = "/content/drive/MyDrive/Modified_Data_6H_CSV"
pollutants = ['so2', 'co', 'o3', 'pm2.5', 'pm10', 'no2']
thresholds = {p: None for p in pollutants}

# Load first 35 files as train/validation, last 36 as test
files = sorted([f for f in os.listdir(data_folder) if f.endswith('.csv')])
train_files = files[:35]
test_files = files[35:]
# print(f"Training files: {len(train_files)}, Testing files: {len(test_files)}")

# Data processing function
def load_and_process(files):
    data = []
    for i, file in enumerate(files):
        # print(f"Processing file {i+1}/{len(files)}: {file}")
        start_time = time.time()
        df = pd.read_csv(os.path.join(data_folder, file), parse_dates=['datacreationdate'])
        df.rename(columns={'datacreationdate': 'time'}, inplace=True)
        df['station'] = file.replace('_6H.csv', '')
        df = df.sort_values(by='time')
        df[pollutants] = df[pollutants].clip(lower=0).ffill()
        df['hour'] = df['time'].dt.hour
        df['month'] = df['time'].dt.month

        for p in pollutants:
            thresholds[p] = df[p].quantile(0.95)
        df['single_anomaly'] = df[pollutants].gt(pd.Series(thresholds)).any(axis=1).astype(int)

        for p in pollutants:
            df[f'{p}_rolling_mean'] = df[p].rolling(window=4).mean()
            df[f'{p}_rolling_std'] = df[p].rolling(window=4).std()

        data.append(df)
        # print(f"Processed {file} in {time.time() - start_time:.2f} seconds")
    return pd.concat(data)

# Load data
start_time = time.time()
train_val_df = load_and_process(train_files)
test_df = load_and_process(test_files)
# print(f"Train+Val shape: {train_val_df.shape}, Test shape: {test_df.shape}")
# print(f"Data loading time: {time.time() - start_time:.2f} seconds")

# Split train and validation data
split_idx = int(len(train_val_df) * 0.8)
train_df = train_val_df.iloc[:split_idx]
val_df = train_val_df.iloc[split_idx:]
# print(f"Train shape: {train_df.shape}, Val shape: {val_df.shape}")

# Features and labels
features = pollutants + ['hour', 'month'] + \
           [f'{p}_rolling_mean' for p in pollutants] + \
           [f'{p}_rolling_std' for p in pollutants]
label = 'single_anomaly'

X_train, y_train = train_df[features].fillna(0), train_df[label]
X_val, y_val = val_df[features].fillna(0), val_df[label]
X_test, y_test = test_df[features].fillna(0), test_df[label]
# print(f"X_train shape: {X_train.shape}, X_test shape: {X_test.shape}")
# print("NaNs in X_train:", X_train.isna().sum().sum())

# Handle imbalance
smote = SMOTE(random_state=42, sampling_strategy=0.5)
start_time = time.time()
X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
# print(f"SMOTE shape: {X_train_resampled.shape}, SMOTE time: {time.time() - start_time:.2f} seconds")

# Train Random Forest + GridSearchCV
param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200],
    'max_depth': [5, 10, 20],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2]
}
tscv = TimeSeriesSplit(n_splits=5)
clf = GridSearchCV(RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42, class_weight='balanced'),
                   param_grid, cv=tscv, scoring='f1')
start_time = time.time()
clf.fit(X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled)
print(f"GridSearchCV time: {time.time() - start_time:.2f} seconds")

# Prediction and evaluation
best_model = clf.best_estimator_
y_pred = best_model.predict(X_test)

print( "Best parameters:", clf.best_params_)
print("Test set evaluation:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred, digits=4))

# Confusion matrix
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues')
plt.title("Confusion Matrix (Test Set)")
plt.xlabel("Predicted")
plt.ylabel("Actual")
plt.show()

# Feature importance
importances = pd.Series(best_model.feature_importances_, index=features)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
sns.barplot(x=importances.values, y=importances.index)
plt.title("Feature Importance")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Save model
model_path = '/content/drive/MyDrive/best_rf_model_35stations.joblib'
joblib.dump(best_model, model_path)
print(f"Model saved to: {model_path}")
